Richardsonian Romanesque</a> <span style="color: white;">............</span>&nbsp; </small></small></b></font><a href="../vocab.html"><b>Illustrated Architecture Dictionary</b></a>


</p>
<blockquote>
	<p align="center"><big style="color: rgb(153, 0, 0);"><big><span style="font-weight: bold;">Richardsonian Romanesque: </span><b>Syrian arch</b></big></big></p>
  <p align="center"><img src="syr.jpg" alt=""></p>
  <table style="text-align: left; width: 90%; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;" border="1" cellpadding="10" cellspacing="1">
    <tbody>
      <tr>
        <td style="vertical-align: top;">
        <div style="text-align: center;"><span style="color: rgb(102, 0, 0); font-weight: bold;">H. H. Richardson</span><br>
        </div>
        <br>
His arches are frequently not truly Romanesque but <a href="https://buffaloah.com/a/archsty/rom/index.html">Syrian</a>, an early Christian form which springs from ground level rather than from a supporting pedestal.<br>
        <br>
        <div style="margin-left: 40px;">- Virginia and Lee McAlester, <span style="font-style: italic;">A Field Guide to American Houses</span>.&nbsp; New York, Alfred A. Knopf, 2000, page 302<br>
        </div>
        </td>
      </tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

	<p>
</p><hr>
